TY  - JOUR
T1  - Management in Perspective Automation: Our Greatest Asset—Our Greatest Problem?
AU  - Megginson, Leon C.
Y1  - 1963/09/01
PY  - 1963
DA  - 1963/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255094
DO  - 10.5465/255094
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 232
EP  - 244
VL  - 6
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article discusses the impact of automation on U.S. business enterprises in 1963. There are two divergent schools of thought in the U.S. regarding automation. One group believes that automation is creating a new problem of national survival. The other faction thinks mechanization is necessary for survival. It is expected that increased mechanization and the move to an economy based on automation will lead to an increased degree of diversification and adaptability on the part of the individual employee.
