TY  - JOUR
T1  - Executive Development as an Instrument of Higher Control
AU  - Scott, William G.
Y1  - 1963/09/01
PY  - 1963
DA  - 1963/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255090
DO  - 10.5465/255090
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 191
EP  - 203
VL  - 6
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article discusses the use of executive development as an instrument of organizational control. Development in this context refers to the planned influence of individual psychological processes. It is the purpose of this development to gain from employees attitudinal commitment to the philosophy, values, and goals of a business organization. A model for a planned program of influence is presented. The organizational learning facets of the plan include altering influences which affect employee attitudes, introducing employees to new values, and crystallization of new attitudes.
